						<summary>

						<p>On the south wall of the central shrine in the Anantēśvarasvāmin temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Parakēsarivarman, who took the head of Vīrapāṇḍya (Āditya II) Year 2: 962 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>Records an undertaking given by the temple officials <hi rend="italic">(dēvakanmigaḷ)</hi> to Araiyaṉ Gēyaviṭaṅkaṉ, a member of <hi rend="italic">(kaikōḷa)</hi> regiment, <hi rend="italic">Siṅgaḷāntaka-tteriñja-kaikkōḷar</hi> to provide a pair of cloth-wreaths <hi rend="italic">(tirupparisaṭṭam)</hi> to the god Mahādēva who is dancing in the stone temple, Tiruvanantiśvaram at Śrī Vīranārāyaṇa-chaturvēdimaṅgalam, a <hi rend="italic">brahmadēyam</hi> on the northern bank (of the river Kāvēri), with the interest of three <hi rend="italic">kāśu</hi> received from him.</p>						

						</summary>
